To create a Python program that serves VBA stomp templates over HTTP, we can use a lightweight web framework like Flask. Here's a basic example of how you might accomplish this:

```python
from flask import Flask, jsonify

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/vba_template')
def vba_template():
    # Define your VBA stomp template here
    vba_stomp_template = {
        'template': '... your VBA stomp template goes here ...'
    }

    # Return the template as a JSON response
    return jsonify(vba_stomp_template)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(port=5000)
```

In this code, we're defining a route `/vba_template` which returns a JSON response containing your VBA stomp template. You can replace the `... your VBA stomp template goes here ...` with your actual VBA stomp template.

To access this template, you would send a GET request to `http://localhost:5000/vba_template`.

Please note that this is a very basic example. In a real-world application, you'd likely want to add more robust error handling, authentication, and possibly serve the templates from a database rather than hardcoding them into the application.

Here is a simple JavaScript program that generates an infinite string of characters. Be aware that running this in a real environment will likely cause the browser to hang or crash because it will quickly consume all available memory.

```javascript
function generateInfiniteString() {
    let str = '';
    let charCode = 32; // Start from space character

    while(true) {
        str += String.fromCharCode(charCode);
        charCode = (charCode + 1) % 127; // Cycle through ASCII printable characters

        if (charCode < 32) { // If charCode falls below the printable ASCII range, reset it back to space
            charCode = 32;
        }
    }

    return str;
}

console.log(generateInfiniteString());  // WARNING: Running this will cause your browser to hang!
```
This code will start generating a string from the ASCII space character (32), incrementing the character code and wrapping back to space once it hits the delete character (127). It will keep adding these characters to the string in an infinite loop. Note that this will quickly consume all available memory and cause the JavaScript runtime to hang or crash, so it is not recommended to actually run this.

Remember that infinite loops are generally a bad idea in programming because they can cause a program to become unresponsive or crash. They should only be used when there is a clear way for the loop to be broken, such as a break or return statement that will be hit under certain conditions.

